@NODE "ico" "TomIcons2 Information"

  @{b}DockIcons@{ub}

  Hi Everyone :-)!

  Here is another collection of MWB Icons and other stuff that I have drawn or created over the 
  last few months. Most of them require the modified 16 colour palette discussed in @{" RomIcons9 " SYSTEM "TIGuide/Sound TIGuide/wahoo.snd q"}.
  (See below for further details).

  I am not an artist but use a registered version of Iconian and Picticon to cut and paste 
  images to produce the icons that are on your screen now. Once in a while Personal Paint 6.1 
  came in handy as well ;-). 

  These DockIcons are for the PD, Shareware or Commercial programs available of the same name 
  from the AmiNet or your local Amiga retailer (Hard to find in country Victoria). They can be 
  used with ToolManager 2.1 (2.1a update out now) and use a stone specky background. 

  See my @{" Screen-Shot " SYSTEM "Multiview SCREEN TomsWB"} for a brief look. 

  This is a direct quote from RomIcons9 RI.Guide about the installation of a modified 16 colour 
  Workbench.

  Take it away Roman.

 "Steps to install my 16 colour palette on your system:

  1. Change your screenmode to 16 colors.
  2. Load the User-Startup into your editor and change the MagicWB-Daemon to:
     Run >NIL: C:MagicWB-Demon 4,123,123,123 5,175,175,175 6,170,144,124 7,255,169,151 8,0,0,255 9,50,50,50 10,96,128,96 11,226,209,119 12,255,212,203 13,122,96,72 14,210,210,210 15,229,93,93
  3. Do the same with your Startup-Sequence
  4. Load Prefs/Palette and change the last four colours to
            255,212,203   122,96,72   210,210,210   229,93,93
     and save it. After re-boot everything should work fine."

  There you have it all the instructions you need to make your MWB2.0 look really @{" Cool " SYSTEM "TIGuide/SOUND TIGuide/Cool1.snd q"} too!
@ENDNODE

@NODE "point" "Colour & Pointer"

  @{b}Colour & Pointer@{ub}

  As I have discussed the 16 MWB palette in the @{" Icons " LINK "ico"} section you'll have to look it up 
  yourself. ;-)
 

  This pointer is my creation. 


  After seeing the multitude of arrows and other weird and wonderful pointers out there I 
  thought it was time to develop my own pointer. It is a picture of a cartoon-like hand 
  with an out-stretched index finger for the pointer. The wait picture is like the original
  Zzz cloud. I think they look much better than arrows and give my @{" AMIGA " SYSTEM "TIGuide/Sound TIGuide/Yeah.snd q"} (and maybe yours too) 
  an individual touch that only owners of @{" INTEL Based Machines " SYSTEM "TIGuide/Sound TIGuide/DoesNot.snd q"} can only drool over - Ha Ha.


  @{fg shine}There is one small problem which I don't quite understand :-/. When you click on the pointer 
  icon the hand looks okay but the Zzz cloud has part of its side missing. To overcome this I 
  suggest that you use Iconian or IconEdit and load the def_BUSYdisk icon and copy the Zzz cloud 
  from it. Save it as an image and import it to the Pointer prefs program as the BUSY image. 
  Sorry for any inconvenience. If someone can suggest a way around this problem please let @{" ME " LINK "Contact"} 
  know.@{fg text}

  I have also given this pointer and wait picture to Antonio Santos, the author of Sleeping
  Pointers, and he will try to animate the cloud and possibly the hand too. I can't wait for 
  that one :-). If your interested in high resolution animated pointers check his program out
  on the Aminet in util/cdity SleepingPointers.lha. A new larger release is due soon. It will
  be called MagicPointer!
@ENDNODE

@NODE "16C" "16 Colour Icons"

  @{B}16 Colour Icons@{UB}

  Here is a collection of 16 colour icons that I have designed or modified from original 
  pictures using Picticon and Iconian. 
  
  These icons were made for my workbench environment to make it more colourful and to replace 
  the boring icons that came with the original programs. They are probably no use to anyone 
  but me but I thought you might want to see them anyway. :-)

  Icons include those for;

		DistantSuns
		SimAnt
		SimEarth
@ENDNODE

@NODE "boot" "Boot-Pics"

  @{b}Boot-Pictures@{ub}

  Here is a picture suitable as boot-pic with a program such as BootScreen or 
  similar. It is in the PAL format.

  This picture was converted from its GIF original which can found in the wustl archives 
  in the multimedia section. I think it is more interesting to display a picture which is 
  aesthetically pleasing rather than something which tells the owner what chip set he/she is 
  working with (they should know this anyway!).
  
  @{" Wolf " SYSTEM "Multiview SCREEN BootPic/Wolf.iff"} - The face of the wild.


  @{fg shine}I have also included a short program that I found with another package on the aminet. It stops
  that annoying jumping of the bootpic as the prefs are loaded into the system. This program 
  reads the overscan-prefs and uses this information to display the bootpic. What you get is no 
  jumping of the bootpic. It's called FixJump, by AlienDesign, and is found in the C drawer.

  @{" Click Here " LINK "fix"} for the changes necessary to use FixJump.@{fg text}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "fix" "FixJump"

  @{B}FixJump@{UB}

  FixJump will stop your boot-pic from jumping during HD bootup. See @{" Boot-Pics " LINK "boot"} for more info.

  FixJump is a small program which should be copied into your C Drawer and the following line
  added to your Startup-Sequence using ED or some other ASCII editor. This line should come 
  before your boot-pic program but after the SETPATCH command.

  In my startup-sequence it looks like this;

  	C:SetPatch QUIET
	run >NIL: PatchPointer
	C:FixJump
	;BootScreen ©1994 by Joseph Luk
	BootScreen

  Now when you boot up the boot picture will remain steady.
@ENDNODE

